    <body>
      <pb n="1"/>
      <p rend="align(right)">
        <placeName>Chicago,</placeName>
        <date>February 24, 1862</date>
      </p>
      <p>
        <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser,</addressee>
        <placeName>Philadelphia.</placeName>
      </p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">Dear sir,</p>
      <p rend="indent(2)">You conduct your paper always in such a<lb/> fair manner that I suppose, I
        shall not ask in<lb/> vain to do me the favor of granting some space, in<lb/> the next
        number of the Occident, to the enclosed card.<lb/> Think what ever you may of my religious
        views &amp;c. I<lb/> shall noll<add>?</add> and will not say anything against your<lb/>
        regarding these views erroneous, if you only consider<lb/> them honestly conceived and
        entertained. But, I<lb/> pray you, do not class me with those vainglorious<lb/> braggarts
        who style themselves Doctors, Professors,<lb/> Reverends &amp;c. without blushing, and who,
        without<lb/> the least reluctance, publicly speak of their own<lb/> selves as the pillars of
        Judaism and the champion<lb/> of Israel. The saying of Nittai the Arbelite
        <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> is a very good maxim, and, therefore, I dislike it<lb/> in the
        highest degree to have even my name mentioned<lb/> in one and the same class with those
        pretentious<lb/> impostors of which there are too many in
        <placeName>America.</placeName></p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">Accept, rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi><hi rend="sub">.</hi> sir, the assurance
        of my high estimation</p>
      <p rend="indent(2)">Very resp'fully, yours</p>
      <p rend="indent(3)">
        <persName role="author">B. Felsenthal.</persName>
      </p>
    </body>
  </text>
